vectorData.altText: 5. The ligamentum venosum is a remnant of the ____________  ____________, which carried fetal blood from the umbilical vein to the inferior vena cava.
That's right! The ductus venosus degenerates postnatally, forming the ligamentum venosum.

The Fetal Circulation
This diagram, from an early edition of Grayâ€™s Anatomy, shows the fetal circulation, and explains the formation of both the round ligament of the liver and the ligamentum venosum.
The round ligament of the liver is a remnant of the umbilical vein, which carried oxygenated blood from the placenta, through the umbilicus, to the fetal liver. It is located in the free edge of the falciform ligament.
The ductus venosus collected blood from the umbilical vein and carried it to the IVC, which delivered it to the right atrium. Postnatally, the ductus venosus degenerates, forming the ligamentum venosum, which you see on the visceral surface of the liver under study.
